@wizardofozzie The `doc.kml` that you linked to is actually invalid KML, which is why `fastkml` is unhappy. 

Specifically, `doc.kml` has several `SimpleField` declarations where the `type="wstring"`. But the official KML documentation is pretty clear on this point; see: https://developers.google.com/kml/documentation/extendeddata#adding-typed-data-to-a-feature

I also ran into a set of KML files -- in my case, directly from `census.gov` -- with invalid `SimpleField` types. I ended up writing a derived class of `kml.KML` as follows:

```python
def LenientKML(kml.KML):
    def append(self, type, name, displayName=None):
        if not self.type_is_valid(type):
            type = self.fix_type(type)
        return super(LenientXML, self).append(type, name, displayName=displayName)

   def type_is_valid(self, type):
        return type in ['string', 'int', 'uint', 'short', 'ushort', 'float', 'double', 'bool']
   
    def fix_type(self, type):
        return type
```

In your case, you might implement:
```python
class MyLenientKML(LenientKML):
    def fix_type(self, type):
        if type is 'wstring':
            type = 'string'
        return type
```

