Making sidebar customizable is to follow the purpose of allowing developers that uses django-jet to have custom admin interfaces corresponding to their needs (that includes end-user dashboard/admin interface).

Template overriding permits only one application per `{% block %}` extend the sidebar (it can also use `{{ block.parent }}` but still is a quiete limited feature). To better respond to our goal, we need a way that allows:
- programmatically extends the sidebar;
- dynamically placing items in it for all applications that requires it;

The best way to do so, IMHO would be using a hook system that features handler's priority. I understand that adding a library for only sidebar extension would be a bit overkill, but IMHO, that would be really great to actually take it as an advantage for more customization; e.g. add actions in display list (per row, per list), or in edit views. This would make django-jet usable for complete and integrated admin interface without having the hassle to jungle with templates.


We can implement our own hook stack, but it actually would repeat the work and furthermore be against the Django's principles of reusability through libraries. There is a library called `django-hooks` that includes template integration of hooks, but it has not been updated for more than two years.

That is for those reasons I've actually wrote the code of `django-foxhook` (that has been made a separate library from another project for the sake of being reusable). I've took advantage of this to implement extra-features comparing to `django-hook` -- some of thinking of this issue:
- template integration;
- customisable and reusable handlers mechanism;
- double priority system: by "always before/after", then by priority;
- drop/get results from handlers;
- function decorator;

We of course can rewrite the entire hook system, but that won't be really interesting for all the reasons of why we use external libraries.

