@matt-peters, on your points:

1. Realistically, this is not going to happen.  It's too complicated to have the code try to decide which things should be saved and which loaded, where pytorch just gives us `state_dict` and `load_state_dict`.  The space savings that you would get from doing this aren't worth the engineering time to make a clean solution here, given that we have lots of other things to do.

2-3. You're right that what you're describing will just work with current code.  It's fine if you want to do it this way.  But I think it might be worth thinking a little more carefully about how to do this more generally.  The cleanest way I can think of to do something like this is to define a `ModelTextFieldEmbedder` that just passes off the embedding to a loaded model.  Then you'd have an `ELMoModel` class that is loaded from an archive, just like any other model, and you just have a single parameter in the main configuration - the path to the model archive.  How the `ELMoModel` works internally is up to you, and you can do whatever you want, as long as it results in a model that can be loaded from a single archive file.  But this way, you get a really simple specification for downstream models that want to use ELMo (or any other model) to replace their text embedder.

